  'bass-worm-texas-rig': {
    slug: 'bass-worm-texas-rig',
    title: 'Bass Texas Rig Guide: Flipping and Pitching Basics',
    h1: 'Largemouth Bass Texas Rig Tactics',
    description: 'Complete guide to Texas rig bass fishing. Covers sinker weight, hook selection, worm types, cover flipping fundamentals, and practical flipping and pitching techniques.',
    lead: 'The Texas rig is the most fundamental and endlessly rewarding rig in bass fishing. A bullet sinker, offset hook, and soft plastic worm combine into a simple package that pulls bass out of the heaviest cover. With superb snag resistance, it handles everything from dense cover to open water. Every bass angler -- from beginner to tournament pro -- should master this rig.',
    sections: [
      {
        heading: 'Texas Rig Setup',
        body: '<p>A Texas rig\'s performance is determined by three component choices.</p><ul><li><strong>Sinker (3.5-14g)</strong>: A bullet-shaped sinker is standard. Tungsten offers superior sensitivity and a slimmer profile for better cover penetration. Lead is affordable and expendable. Choose weight based on cover density: 3.5-5g for light cover, 7g for medium cover, 10-14g for heavy cover.</li><li><strong>Hook</strong>: Offset hooks in #1/0 to #5/0. Match hook size to worm size: #2/0-#3/0 for 4-inch worms, #4/0-#5/0 for 5-6 inch worms. Wide-gap styles improve hookup rates.</li><li><strong>Worm</strong>: Craw, hog, stick, and creature baits are all staples. Select based on cover type and water clarity.</li></ul><p><strong>Pegging</strong>: Whether or not you peg (fix) the sinker to the hook using a toothpick or rubber stopper changes the rig\'s behavior. Pegging improves cover penetration by keeping the sinker and worm as one unit. Without a peg, the sinker and worm separate on the fall, producing a more natural descent.</p>',
      },
      {
        heading: 'Cover Flipping Fundamentals',
        body: '<p>The Texas rig\'s specialty is <strong>cover fishing</strong> -- placing the rig deep into bass-holding cover and working it along the bottom to draw a bite.</p><p><strong>Flipping</strong>: A close-range underhand technique using a pendulum motion. Strip line by hand while swinging the rod up and down, dropping the rig into cover 5-10 meters away with minimal splash. Highly efficient for rapidly probing scattered cover.</p><p><strong>Pitching</strong>: Disengage the reel\'s spool, side-arm the rod in a low arc to cast on a flat trajectory. Reaches farther than flipping (10-20m) with excellent accuracy. The quiet entry is effective on pressured bass.</p><p><strong>Bottom action</strong>: After the rig hits bottom, shake the rod tip in short pulses (2-3 seconds), lift 10-20cm, let it fall, touch bottom, and shake again. The worm comes alive on the bottom, triggering a bass\'s predatory instinct. If no bite comes within 5-10 seconds, move to the next piece of cover. Maintaining this tempo is crucial.</p>',
      },
      {
        heading: 'Worm Selection by Type',
        body: '<p><strong>Craw baits (3.5-4.5 inch)</strong>: Crawfish-imitating shapes are the classic Texas rig pairing. The paddles flap on the fall, delivering maximum appeal inside cover. Especially effective during the spring spawn.</p><p><strong>Hog baits (3.5-5 inch)</strong>: Bulkier versions of craws with added legs and arms. Their extra displacement stands out around structure. Choose these when you need maximum presence.</p><p><strong>Stick baits (5-7 inch)</strong>: Simple straight shapes with minimal vibration for a natural presentation. They dominate in pressured fisheries and clear water. Rotate with a neko rig for variety.</p><p><strong>Creature baits (3.5-5 inch)</strong>: Fantasy shapes mimicking various organisms -- insects, lizards, and more. Multiple arms and tails produce complex water displacement. The standard choice for punching through matted vegetation with a heavy sinker.</p>',
      },
      {
        heading: 'Tackle Setup',
        body: '<p><strong>Baitcasting gear</strong> is mandatory. You need the power to wrench bass out of cover, which spinning tackle cannot deliver.</p><p><strong>Light Texas (3.5-7g)</strong>: MH to H power baitcasting rod, 6.8-7 feet. Reel gear ratio 6-7:1. Fluorocarbon 12-16lb. For light cover and visible bass approaches.</p><p><strong>Heavy Texas (7-14g)</strong>: H power rod, 7-7.6 feet. High-gear reel at 7-8:1. Fluorocarbon 16-20lb. For punching heavy cover -- you need the power to instantly pull bass away from obstacles.</p><p><strong>Punching (14-28g)</strong>: XH power flipping rod, 7.6 feet or longer. PE 5-8. For blasting through matted surface vegetation to reach bass hiding underneath. The heaviest Texas rig setup.</p><p><strong>Hookset</strong>: Bites feel like a subtle "tick" or "thud." Reel down to take up slack, then drive the rod upward with a powerful sweep set. The denser the cover, the harder you need to set.</p>',
      },
    ],
    faq: [
      { question: 'What is the best worm to start with for Texas rigging?', answer: 'A 4-inch craw worm in green pumpkin with a 5g bullet sinker and #3/0 offset hook is the ideal starter kit. Drop it along seawalls or into gaps in riprap and bass will eat it. Focus on learning snag avoidance and hookset timing with this setup.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between a Texas rig and a free rig?', answer: 'On a Texas rig, the sinker threads onto the line and moves with the worm as a unit. On a free rig, the sinker hits bottom first and the worm then falls weightlessly behind it. The Texas rig prioritizes cover penetration, while the free rig emphasizes a natural fall presentation. Use each according to the situation.' },
      { question: 'How do I choose Texas rig worm colors?', answer: 'Green pumpkin is the single most versatile color. In clear water, go with watermelon or smoke tones. In stained water, use black-blue or junebug (dark purple). During the spawn, red and orange accents can be especially effective.' },
    ],
  },

