  'chimu-topwater': {
    slug: 'chimu-topwater',
    title: 'Black Sea Bream Topwater Guide: Popper Tactics',
    h1: 'Black Sea Bream Topwater Fishing Tactics',
    description: 'Complete guide to topwater fishing for black sea bream (kurodai/chinu). Covers popper and pencil bait techniques, spot-by-spot strategies for tidal flats, rivers, and harbors.',
    lead: 'Topwater fishing for black sea bream (chinu/kurodai) is a summer tradition among Japanese anglers. The explosive surface strikes are unforgettable, and once you experience it, you\'re hooked. This guide covers the techniques for drawing black sea bream to the surface with poppers and pencil baits across tidal flats, brackish estuaries, and harbors.',
    sections: [
      {
        heading: 'Lure Selection for Chinu Topwater',
        body: '<p>Two lure types dominate chinu topwater fishing: <strong>poppers</strong> and <strong>pencil baits</strong>.</p><ul><li><strong>Poppers (60-70mm)</strong>: The cupped face grabs water to produce popping sounds and splash. Their strong search ability makes them ideal for covering vast tidal flats and open water.</li><li><strong>Pencil baits (60-80mm)</strong>: The dog-walk action swings the lure side to side. More subtle than a popper, they excel under pressure and in clear water.</li></ul><p>The standard size range for chinu topwater is 60-70mm. Although black sea bream have relatively large mouths, they are targeting crustaceans and small baitfish when feeding on the surface, so smaller lures tend to draw more bites. A weight of 7-12g casts comfortably during wading on tidal flats.</p>',
      },
      {
        heading: 'Action Fundamentals',
        body: '<p><strong>Popper technique</strong>: Use short, gentle twitches to produce a quiet "pop, pop" sound. Unlike sea bass topwater, chinu topwater calls for restrained, subtle pops rather than dramatic splashes. The basic cadence is 2-3 pops followed by a 3-5 second pause. Most bites come during the pause.</p><p><strong>Pencil bait technique</strong>: Create slack in the line, then sweep the rod sideways to produce a dog-walk action. Short, tight walks with minimal forward travel are most effective for black sea bream. Work in sets of 5-6 walks followed by a 2-3 second pause.</p><p><strong>Hookset timing</strong>: A chinu topwater strike often appears as a gentle "bulge" on the surface rather than an explosive blowup. Setting instantly will pull the lure away. Wait until the lure is pulled under the surface before setting -- the delayed hookset is the iron rule. Stay patient.</p>',
      },
      {
        heading: 'Spot-by-Spot Strategies',
        body: '<p><strong>Tidal flats</strong>: The premier chinu topwater venue. Target shallow flats with 30cm to 1m of water where black sea bream cruise in to feed on crustaceans. The rising tide after low water is prime time, as fish push onto the flat with the incoming water. Wade out and fan-cast across the expanse.</p><p><strong>Rivers (brackish zones)</strong>: Bridge pilings and seawalls encrusted with oyster shells are key holding spots. Run lures tight to structure. Tidal fluctuations shift the fish\'s position, so checking the tide chart is essential.</p><p><strong>Harbors</strong>: Target the edges of breakwalls, boat ramps, and oyster/mussel belts on seawalls. Black sea bream cruise in to feed on shellfish clinging to vertical surfaces. A parallel cast along the wall -- keeping the lure running close to the structure -- is the most effective approach.</p>',
      },
      {
        heading: 'Season and Tackle',
        body: '<p>Chinu topwater peaks from <strong>June through September</strong>. Once water temperatures exceed 22°C, black sea bream move into the shallows and become responsive to surface lures. July and August are the absolute best months, when warm water pushes activity to maximum and double-digit catches in a single session are possible. After October, cooling water gradually shuts down the topwater bite.</p><p><strong>Tackle</strong>: A dedicated chinu rod or a light-class sea bass rod, 7-8 feet. A softer rod helps embed the hook in the fish\'s hard mouth. Use a 2500-3000 size reel with PE 0.6-0.8 mainline and 8-12lb fluorocarbon leader. Black sea bream pull hard toward structure, so err on the heavier side with the leader to avoid break-offs.</p>',
      },
    ],
    faq: [
      { question: 'What time of day is best for chinu topwater?', answer: 'Early morning (around sunrise) and dusk are peak activity windows. On tidal flats, tidal movement matters more than clock time -- the incoming tide that pushes black sea bream onto the shallow flat is the biggest opportunity. In midsummer, daytime fishing is also productive.' },
      { question: 'What if black sea bream follow the lure but won\'t commit?', answer: 'Downsize the lure (70mm to 60mm), switch to a clear or ghost color, soften the popping sound, and extend the pause duration to 5-10 seconds. Black sea bream often trail behind and study a lure before striking, so slowing down your cadence can make the difference.' },
      { question: 'What popper colors work best for chinu topwater?', answer: 'Clear and ghost patterns are the all-around best. Black sea bream have sharp eyesight and respond well to realistic finishes. In murky water, switch to chartreuse or gold for added visibility. Solid black also performs well on tidal flats, where it creates a strong silhouette against the shallow backdrop.' },
    ],
  },
